# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: forward-plus-rendering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] In computer graphics, **fixed-function** is a term primarily used to describe 3D graphics APIs and GPUs designed prior to the advent of programmable shaders.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] The term is also used to describe APIs and graphics pipelines that do not allow users to change its underlying processing techniques, hence the word 'fixed'.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] Fixed-function can also refer to graphics processing techniques that employ non-programmable dedicated hardware, like the use of ROPs to rasterize an image.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] Although the exact origin of the term 'fixed-function' is unclear, the first known graphics hardware that is considered to be fixed-function is the IBM 8514/A graphics add-in-board from 1987.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] When compared to other graphics hardware of its time, particularly hardware that made use of the RISC-based TMS34010, the 8514/A has similar processing speeds while also launching at a significantly less expensive price point.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] However, those benefits came at a cost of programming flexibility, as the 8514/A was designed more like an ASIC than its competition that were similar to general-purpose CPUs.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] Following the 8514/A, the most powerful dedicated graphics hardware of the 1990s have pipelines that are not programmable, only configurable to a limited degree.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] This means that host CPUs have no direct influence on how its GPUs will process vertex and rasterization operations, beyond issuing indirect commands and transferring data bidirectionally from CPU-sided RAM to GPU-sided VRAM.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] As more hardware with this fixed-function design released, 3D graphics API developers of the 90s mimicked the nature of available hardware in their own software design by creating logical graphics pipelines that are only configurable and non-programmable.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] Graphics APIs of this time, notably OpenGL and early versions DirectX (Direct3D), are themselves retroactively referred to as fixed-function as they ultimately share many design characteristics with the fixed-function hardware they targeted.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] Historically fixed-function APIs consisted of a set of function entry points that would approximately or directly map to dedicated logic for their named purpose in GPUs designed to support them.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] As shader based GPUs and APIs evolved, fixed-function APIs were implemented by graphics driver engineers using the more general purpose shading architecture.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] This approach served as a segue that would continue providing the fixed-function API abstraction most developers were experienced with while allowing further development and enhancements of the newer shader-based architectures.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] OpenGL, OpenGL ES and DirectX are all 3D graphics APIs that went through the transition from the fixed-function programming model to the shader-based programming model.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] Even after the popularization of programmable shaders and graphics pipelines, certain GPU features would remain non-programmable to optimize for speed over flexibility.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] For example, the NVIDIA GeForce 6 series GPUs delegated early culling, rasterization, MSAA, depth queries, texture mapping and more to fixed-function implementations.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] The CPU does not direct the GPU how to specifically process these operations; these features can only be configured to a limited degree.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] In a fixed-function pipeline, the stages of the graphics pipeline are pre-defined and can be configured by the programmer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] A shader-based pipeline allows programmers to replace some of these stages with custom programs called shaders, which allows for more sophisticated rendering techniques and greater flexibility.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/fixed-function] However, even modern shader-based pipelines are not wholly programmable; APIs such as OpenGL and Direct3D 12 define graphics pipelines that combine programmable shader stages with fixed-function operations.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] A hidden-surface determination algorithm is a solution to the visibility problem, which was one of the first major problems in the field of 3D computer graphics.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] The process of hidden-surface determination is sometimes called **hiding**, and such an algorithm is sometimes called a **hider**.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] When referring to line rendering it is known as hidden-line removal.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Hidden-surface determination is necessary to render a scene correctly, so that one may not view features hidden behind the model itself, allowing only the naturally viewable portion of the graphic to be visible.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Hidden-surface determination is a process that identifies which surfaces are not visible to the user (for example, because they lie behind opaque objects such as walls).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Despite advances in hardware capability, rendering algorithms require substantial computational resources.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] By deciding that certain surfaces do not need to be rendered because they are not visible, rendering engines can improve efficiency, allowing the rendering of large world spaces.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] There are many techniques for hidden-surface determination, but they generally rely on sorting the surfaces based on their distance from the viewer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Sorting large quantities of graphics primitives can be computationally-expensive and is usually done by divide and conquer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] The different hidden-surface determination techniques differ, in part, through the way in which the space is partitioned prior to sorting.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] A rendering pipeline typically entails the following steps: projection, clipping, and rasterization.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] is used) is checked against an existing depth value.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] If the current pixel is behind the pixel in the Z-buffer, the pixel is rejected, otherwise, it is shaded and its depth value replaces the one in the Z-buffer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Z-buffering supports dynamic scenes easily and is currently implemented efficiently in graphics hardware.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Z-buffering requires up to 4 bytes per pixel, and can have a substantial computational cost since the rasterization algorithm needs to check each rasterized sample against the Z-buffer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] , these approaches store information about already displayed segments for each line of the screen (in contrast of storing each pixel as is the case for Z-buffering).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] New polygons are then cut against already displayed segments that would hide them.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] An S-buffer can display unsorted polygons, while a C-buffer requires polygons to be displayed from the nearest to the furthest.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Because the C-buffer technique does not require a pixel to be drawn more than once, the process is slightly faster.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Polygons are displayed from the nearest to the furthest.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] New polygons are clipped against already displayed polygons' edges, creating new polygons to display, then storing the additional edges.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Such an approach is harder to implement than S/C/Z-buffers, but it scales much better with increased image resolution.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] The drawbacks are the computational cost of the sorting step and the fact that visual artifacts can occur.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] This algorithm can fail for general scenes, as it cannot handle polygons in various common configurations, such as surfaces that intersect each other.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] This technique divides a scene along planes corresponding to polygon boundaries.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] The subdivision is constructed in such a way as to provide an unambiguous depth ordering from any point in the scene when the BSP tree is traversed.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] The main disadvantage of the technique is the high computational cost of the construction of the BSP tree.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] As a result, this approach is less suitable for scenes consisting of dynamic geometry.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] The advantage of BSP is that the data is pre-sorted and error-free, and can be used as input for the previously mentioned algorithms.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Note that the BSP is not a solution to hidden-surface removal, only an aid.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Ray tracing attempts to model the path of light rays to a viewpoint by tracing rays from the viewpoint into the scene.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Although not a hidden-surface removal algorithm as such, it implicitly solves the hidden-surface removal problem by finding the nearest surface along each view-ray.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Effectively this approach is equivalent to sorting all the geometry on a per-pixel basis.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] This algorithm divides the screen into smaller areas and sorts triangles within these.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] If there is ambiguity (i.e., polygons overlap in-depth extent within these areas), then further subdivision occurs.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] At the limit, the subdivision may occur down to the pixel level.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] A related area to visible-surface determination is *culling*, which usually happens before visible-surface determination in a rendering pipeline.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Primitives or batches of primitives can be rejected in their entirety, which *usually* reduces the computational load in a rendering system.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] The viewing frustum is a geometric representation of the volume visible to the virtual camera.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Naturally, objects outside this volume will not be visible in the final image, so they are discarded.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Often, objects lie on the boundary of the viewing frustum.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] These objects are cut into pieces along this boundary in a process called clipping, and the pieces that lie outside the frustum are discarded as there is no place to draw them.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] With 3D objects, some of the object's surface is facing the camera, and the rest is facing away from the camera, i.e. is on the backside of the object, hindered by the front side.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] If the object is completely opaque, those surfaces never need to be drawn.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] These surfaces are determined by the vertex winding order: if the triangle drawn has its vertices in clockwise order on the projection plane when facing the camera, they switch into counter-clockwise order when the surface turns away from the camera.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Incidentally, this approach also makes the objects completely transparent when the viewpoint camera is located inside them, because then all the surfaces of the object are facing away from the camera and are culled by the renderer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] To prevent this artifact, the object must be set as double-sided (i.e. no back-face culling is done) or have separate inside surfaces.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Often, objects are so far away that they do not contribute significantly to the final image.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] These objects are thrown away if their screen projection is too small.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Objects that are entirely behind other opaque objects may be culled.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] This is a very popular mechanism to speed up the rendering of large scenes that have a moderate to high depth complexity.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] A popular theme in the visible surface determination literature is divide and conquer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] The Warnock algorithm pioneered dividing the screen.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Beam tracing is a ray-tracing approach that divides the visible volumes into beams.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Various screen-space subdivision approaches reduce the number of primitives considered per region, e.g. tiling, or screen-space BSP clipping.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Tiling may be used as a preprocess to other techniques.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Z-buffer hardware may typically include a coarse "hi-Z", against which primitives can be rejected early without rasterization.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Such an approach is a form of occlusion culling.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] Bounding volume hierarchies (BVHs) are often used to subdivide the scene's space (examples are the BSP tree, the octree and the kd-tree).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] This approach allows visibility determination to be performed hierarchically: if a node in the tree is considered to be *invisible*, then all of its child nodes are also invisible, and no further processing is necessary (they can all be rejected by the renderer).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] If a node is considered *visible*, then each of its children needs to be evaluated.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/frustum-culling] This traversal is effectively a tree walk, where invisibility/occlusion or reaching a leaf node determines whether to stop or whether to recurse, respectively.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Creating a 3D image for display consists of a series of steps.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] First, the objects to be displayed are loaded into memory from individual *models*.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] The system then applies mathematical functions to transform the models into a common coordinate system, the *world view*.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] From this world view, a series of polygons (typically triangles) is created that approximates the original models as seen from a particular viewpoint, the *camera*.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Next, a compositing system produces an image by rendering the triangles and applying *textures* to the outside.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Textures are small images that are painted onto the triangles to produce realism.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] The resulting image is then combined with various special effects, and moved into a frame buffer, which video hardware then scans to produce the displayed image.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] This basic conceptual layout is known as the *display pipeline*.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Each of these steps increases the amount of memory needed to hold the resulting image.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] By the time it reaches the end of the pipeline the images are so large that typical graphics card designs often use specialized high-speed memory and a very fast computer bus to provide the required bandwidth to move the image in and out of the various sub-components of the pipeline.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] This sort of support is possible on dedicated graphics cards, but as power and size budgets become more limited, providing enough bandwidth becomes expensive in design terms.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Tiled renderers address this concern by breaking down the image into sections known as tiles, and rendering each one separately.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] This reduces the amount of memory needed during the intermediate steps, and the amount of data being moved about at any given time.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] To do this, the system sorts the triangles making up the geometry by location, allowing to quickly find which triangles overlap the tile boundaries.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] It then loads just those triangles into the rendering pipeline, performs the various rendering operations in the GPU, and sends the result to the frame buffer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Very small tiles can be used, 16×16 and 32×32 pixels are popular tile sizes, which makes the amount of memory and bandwidth required in the internal stages small as well.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] And because each tile is independent, it naturally lends itself to simple parallelization.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] In a typical tiled renderer, geometry must first be transformed into screen space and assigned to screen-space tiles.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] This requires some storage for the lists of geometry for each tile.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] In early tiled systems, this was performed by the CPU, but all modern hardware contains hardware to accelerate this step.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] The list of geometry can also be sorted front to back, allowing the GPU to use hidden surface removal to avoid processing pixels that are hidden behind others, saving on memory bandwidth for unnecessary texture lookups.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] There are two main disadvantages of the tiled approach.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] One is that some triangles may be drawn several times if they overlap several tiles.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] This means the total rendering time would be higher than an immediate-mode rendering system.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] There are also possible issues when the tiles have to be stitched together to make a complete image, but this problem was solved long ago.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] More difficult to solve is that some image techniques are applied to the frame as a whole, and these are difficult to implement in a tiled render where the idea is to not have to work with the entire frame.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] These tradeoffs are well known, and of minor consequence for systems where the advantages are useful; tiled rendering systems are widely found in handheld computing devices.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Tiled rendering should not be confused with tiled/nonlinear framebuffer addressing schemes, which make adjacent pixels also adjacent in memory.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] These addressing schemes are used by a wide variety of architectures, not just tiled renderers.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Much of the early work on tiled rendering was done as part of the Pixel Planes 5 architecture (1989).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] The Pixel Planes 5 project validated the tiled approach and invented a lot of the techniques now viewed as standard for tiled renderers.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] It is the work most widely cited by other papers in the field.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] The tiled approach was also known early in the history of software rendering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Implementations of Reyes rendering often divide the image into "tile buckets".
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Early in the development of desktop GPUs, several companies developed tiled architectures.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Over time, these were largely supplanted by immediate-mode GPUs with fast custom external memory systems.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Due to the relatively low external memory bandwidth, and the modest amount of on-chip memory required, tiled rendering is a popular technology for embedded GPUs.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Vivante produces mobile GPUs which have tightly coupled frame buffer memory (similar to the Xbox 360 GPU described above).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/tiled-rendering] Although this can be used to render parts of the screen, the large size of the rendered regions means that they are not usually described as using a tile-based architecture.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] A **z-buffer**, also known as a **depth buffer**, is a type of data buffer used in computer graphics to store the depth information of fragments.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] The values stored represent the distance to the camera, with 0 being the closest.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] The encoding scheme may be flipped with the highest number being the value closest to camera.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] In a 3D-rendering pipeline, when an object is projected on the screen, the depth (z-value) of a generated fragment in the projected screen image is compared to the value already stored in the buffer (**depth test**), and replaces it if the new value is closer.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] It works in tandem with the rasterizer, which computes the colored values.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] The fragment output by the rasterizer is saved if it is not overlapped by another fragment.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Z-buffering is a technique used in almost all contemporary computers, laptops, and mobile phones for generating 3D computer graphics.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] The primary use now is for video games, which require fast and accurate processing of 3D scenes.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Determining what should be displayed on the screen and what should be omitted is a multi-step process utilising various techniques.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Using a z-buffer is the final step in this process.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] If the z-value is further away than the value in the z-buffer, the fragment is discarded.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] This is repeated for all objects and surfaces in the scene (often in parallel).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] In the end, the z-buffer will allow correct reproduction of the usual depth perception: a close object hides one further away.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] The granularity of a z-buffer has a great influence on the scene quality: the traditional 16-bit z-buffer can result in artifacts (called "z-fighting" or **stitching**) when two objects are very close to each other.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] A more modern 24-bit or 32-bit z-buffer behaves much better, although the problem cannot be eliminated without additional algorithms.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] An 8-bit z-buffer is almost never used since it has too little precision.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Z-buffer data obtained from rendering a surface from a light's point-of-view permits the creation of shadows by the shadow mapping technique.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Z-buffering was first described in 1974 by Wolfgang Straßer in his PhD thesis on fast algorithms for rendering occluded objects.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] A similar solution to determining overlapping polygons is the painter's algorithm, which is capable of handling non-opaque scene elements, though at the cost of efficiency and incorrect results.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Z-buffers are often implemented in hardware within consumer graphics cards.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Z-buffering is also used (implemented as software as opposed to hardware) for producing computer-generated special effects for films.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Even with small enough granularity, quality problems may arise when precision in the z-buffer's distance values are not spread evenly over distance.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Nearer values are much more precise (and hence can display closer objects better) than values that are farther away.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Generally, this is desirable, but sometimes it will cause artifacts to appear as objects become more distant.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] A variation on z-buffering which results in more evenly distributed precision is called **w-buffering** (see below).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] At the start of a new scene, the z-buffer must be cleared to a defined value, usually 1.0, because this value is the upper limit (on a scale of 0 to 1) of depth, meaning that no object is present at this point through the viewing frustum.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] The invention of the z-buffer concept is most often attributed to Edwin Catmull, although Wolfgang Straßer described this idea in his 1974 Ph.D. thesis months before Catmull's invention.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] On more recent PC graphics cards (1999–2005), z-buffer management uses a significant chunk of the available memory bandwidth.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Super Smash Bros. and F-Zero X are two Nintendo 64 games that minimized z-buffering to increase framerates.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Several Factor 5 games also minimized or omitted z-buffering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] On the Nintendo 64 z-Buffering can consume up to 4x as much bandwidth as opposed to not using z-buffering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Mechwarrior 2 on PC supported resolutions up to 800 × 600 on the original 4 MB 3dfx Voodoo due to not using z-buffering.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] In rendering, z-culling is early pixel elimination based on depth, a method that provides an increase in performance when rendering of hidden surfaces is costly.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] It is a direct consequence of z-buffering, where the depth of each pixel candidate is compared to the depth of the existing geometry behind which it might be hidden.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] When using a z-buffer, a pixel can be culled (discarded) as soon as its depth is known, which makes it possible to skip the entire process of lighting and texturing a pixel that would not be visible anyway.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Also, time-consuming pixel shaders will generally not be executed for the culled pixels.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] This makes z-culling a good optimization candidate in situations where fillrate, lighting, texturing, or pixel shaders are the main bottlenecks.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] While z-buffering allows the geometry to be unsorted, sorting polygons by increasing depth (thus using a reverse painter's algorithm) allows each screen pixel to be rendered fewer times.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] As such, a reverse painter's algorithm cannot be used as an alternative to z-culling (without strenuous re-engineering), except as an optimization to z-culling.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] For example, an optimization might be to keep polygons sorted according to x/y-location and z-depth to provide bounds, in an effort to quickly determine if two polygons might possibly have an occlusion interaction.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] The range of depth values in camera space to be rendered is often defined between a ${\textit {near}}$ and ${\textit {far}}$ value of z .
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] where z is the old value of z in camera space, and is sometimes called w or $w'$ .
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] The resulting values of $z'$ are normalized between the values of –1 and 1, where the ${\textit {near}}$ plane is at –1 and the ${\mathit {far}}$ plane is at 1.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Values outside of this range correspond to points which are not in the viewing frustum, and shouldn't be rendered.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Typically, these values are stored in the z-buffer of the hardware graphics accelerator in fixed point format.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] This formula can be inverted and derived in order to calculate the z-buffer resolution (the "granularity" mentioned earlier).
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] The z-buffer resolution in terms of camera space would be the incremental value resulted from the smallest change in the integer stored in the z-buffer, which is +1 or –1.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] This shows that the values of $z'$ are grouped much more densely near the ${\textit {near}}$ plane, and much more sparsely farther away, resulting in better precision closer to the camera.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] The smaller $near$ is, the less precision there is far away—having the $near$ plane set too closely is a common cause of undesirable rendering artifacts in more distant objects.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] To implement a z-buffer, the values of $z'$ are linearly interpolated across screen space between the vertices of the current polygon, and these intermediate values are generally stored in the z-buffer in fixed point format.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] To implement a w-buffer, the old values of z in camera space, or w , are stored in the buffer, generally in floating point format.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] However, these values cannot be linearly interpolated across screen space from the vertices—they usually have to be inverted, interpolated, and then inverted again.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] The resulting values of w , as opposed to $z'$ , are spaced evenly between ${\textit {near}}$ and ${\textit {far}}$ .
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] There are implementations of the w-buffer that avoid the inversions altogether.
[src:forward-plus-rendering/z-buffering] Whether a z-buffer or w-buffer results in a better image depends on the application.
